SIMPLE: period
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Period
<hw>Pe"ri*od</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>periodus</ets>, Gr. <grk>peri`odos</grk> a going round, a way
round, a circumference, a period of time; <grk>peri`</grk> round, about
+ <grk>"odo`s</grk> a way: cf. F. <ets>p⟦eacute⟧riode</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A portion of time as limited and determined by some
recurring or cyclic phenomenon, as by the completion of a revolution of
one of the heavenly bodies; a division of time, as a series of years,
months, or days, in which something is completed, and ready to
recommence and go on in the same order; <as>as, the <ex>period</ex> of
the sun, or the earth, or a comet; the <ex>period</ex> of an
electromagnetic wave is the time interval between maxima</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A stated and recurring
interval of time; more generally, an interval of time specified or left
indefinite; a certain series of years, months, days, or the like; a
time; a cycle; an age; an epoch; <as>as, the <ex>period</ex> of the
Roman republic</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How by art to make plants more lasting than their ordinary
<qex>period</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>One of the great divisions of
geological time; <as>as, the Tertiary <ex>period</ex>; the Glacial
<ex>period</ex></as>. See the <xex>Chart</xex> of
<er>Geology</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The termination or completion of a revolution,
cycle, series of events, single event, or act; hence, a limit; a bound;
an end; a conclusion.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So spake the archangel Michael; then paused,⟦br⟧
As at the world's great <qex>period</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Evils which shall never end till eternity hath a
<qex>period</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the <qex>period</qex> of my ambition.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>A complete sentence, from one
full stop to another; esp., a well-proportioned, harmonious
sentence.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Devolved his rounded <xex>periods</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Periods</qex> are beautiful when they are not too long.</q>
<rj><qau>B. Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>period</xex>, according to Heyse, is a compound
sentence consisting of a protasis and apodosis; according to Becker, it
is the appropriate form for the coordinate propositions related by
antithesis or causality.</note> <rj><au>Gibbs.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>The punctuation point [.] that
marks the end of a complete sentence, or of an abbreviated
word.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>One of several similar sets of
figures or terms usually marked by points or commas placed at regular
intervals, as in numeration, in the extraction of roots, and in
circulating decimals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1067 --></p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The time of the exacerbation and
remission of a disease, or of the paroxysm and intermission.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A complete musical
sentence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Sports)</fld> <def>One of the specified time
intervals into which a game is divided; <as>as, there are three
<ex>periods</ex> in a hockey game</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Education)</fld> <def>One of the specified time
intervals into which the academic day is divided; <as>as, my calculus
class is in the first <ex>period</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>The time interval during which a woman is
menstruating, or the event of a single menstruation; <as>as, her
<ex>period</ex> was late this month</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The period</b></col>, <cd>the present or current time, as
distinguished from all other times.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Time; date; epoch; era; age; duration; limit;
bound; end; conclusion; determination.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Period</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Period
<hw>Pe"ri*od</hw> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧"r⟦icr⟧*⟦ucr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<def>To put an end to.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Period</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Period
<hw>Pe"ri*od</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To come to a period; to
conclude. <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧You may <xex>period</xex> upon
this, that,⟦rdquo⟧ etc.</def> <rj><au>Felthman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Periodate</ent>⟦br⟧
